<DOC><DOCNO> AP890811-0172 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-11-89 2220EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Canada-Bravery     08-11 0153</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Canada-Bravery,0159</SECOND><HEAD>Canada Gives American Firefighter Award for Bravery</HEAD><DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Canada announced Friday that an Americanfirefighter has been awarded the Star of Courage for saving threepeople, including a 5-year-old child, from a burning car.   Richard Shiah, of Niagara Falls, N.Y., was among 14 peopleawarded bravery decorations Friday by Gov. Gen. Jeanne Sauve. Theother 13 were Canadians.   In May 1988, Shiah saved three members of a family when theirtruck and trailer carrying fuel crashed and burst into flames nearFonthill, Ontario.   Shiah, who suffered severe facial burns during the rescue, isone of only 315 people to receive the Star of Courage.   The governor general, Canada's ceremonial head of state, willpresent the bravery awards at a ceremony later this year.   Since 1972, the governor general has awarded 1,278 decorationsfor bravery, including 15 Crosses of Valor, 315 Stars of Courage,and 948 Medals of Bravery.</TEXT></DOC>